SIMPLE: windrow
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Windrow
<hw>Wind"row`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Wind</ets> +
<ets>row</ets>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>A row or line of hay raked together for the purpose
of being rolled into cocks or heaps.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Sheaves of grain set up in a row, one against
another, that the wind may blow between them.</def>
<mark>[Eng.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The green border of a field, dug up in order to
carry the earth on other land to mend it.</def> <mark>[Eng.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Windrow</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Windrow
<hw>Wind"row</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Windrowed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Windrowing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To arrange in lines or
windrows, as hay when newly made.</def> <rj><au>Forby.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Wind-shaken</ent>⟦br⟧
